"Hertfordshire, England","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Hopton Castle, Shropshire, England":"Hopton Castle, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mortimer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Mortemer in Seine-Maritime, France, so called from Old French <i>mort(e)</i> ‘dead’ + <i>mer</i> ‘sea’, probably referring to a stagnant pond or drained swamp.","Irish (of Norman origin): the Norman surname in sense 1 above was taken to Ireland from England in the medieval period, where it has also been adopted by bearers of the Gaelic surnames <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> and <b>ÓMuircheartaigh</b>, commonly Anglicized as <b>McMurty</b> and <b>Mortagh</b>. Compare   McMurdo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mortimore","meanings":["English (Devon; of Norman origin): variant of   Mortimer  ."]},{"name":"McMurdo","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> or <b>Mac Muircheartaich</b>, ‘son of Muircheartach’, a personal name meaning ‘sea-ruler’. In Scotland the name was often lenited to give   McCurdy  . Compare   Murdoch   and   Moriarty  . The name was also used to Anglicize <i>Mac Murchaidh</i> (see   McMorrow  )."]}]},{"name":"Joanne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, and so a doublet of   Joan .  This too was revived as a given name in its own right in the first half of the 20th century. It has to some extent been influenced by the independently formed combination <i>Jo Anne</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Johanne","meanings":["and Norwegian feminine form of   Johan ."]},{"name":"Joann","meanings":["From Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, and so a doublet of   Joan .  This too was revived as a given name in its own right in the first half of the 20th century. It has to some extent been influenced by the independently formed combination <i>Jo Anne</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joanne de Mortimer was born about 1364, in Wigmore, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Walter de Mortimer, was 85 and her mother, Joan de Joinville, was 30. She married Thomas Hopton in 1387, in Hertfordshire, England. She died after 1396."},"et":{"Abt 1364–after 1396":"umbes 1364–pärast 1396","1364–1396":"1364–1396","1362–1387":"1362–1387","1388–1445":"1388–1445","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","1335":"1335","1445":"1445","1388":"1388","Abt 1364":"umbes 1364","1387":"1387","1364":"1364","1396":"1396","1362":"1362","after 1396":"pärast 1396","1280":"1280","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Hopton Castle, Shropshire, England":"Hopton Castle, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1364–after 1396":"noin 1364–1396 jälkeen","1364–1396":"1364–1396","1362–1387":"1362–1387","1388–1445":"1388–1445","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1335–Female":"1335–Kuoll